collections.name: Portal to Infinity
collections.description:
Some art is meant to be seen. This one is meant to be felt.

It doesn’t just sit there; it pulls you in. The green mist moves like a whisper, carrying forgotten secrets. The eye at the center meets yours—not as a stranger, but as something that has always known you. The hands reach forward, as if offering something unseen yet deeply familiar.

And then you see them. The first ones. A man and a woman, frozen at the crossroads of destiny. Between them, the choice that altered existence. The forbidden fruit—the symbol of knowledge, risk, and consequence.

This isn’t decoration. It’s an echo of something ancient, something that has always been inside you. It doesn’t just ask to be looked at—it demands to be remembered.

? This is not just art. It’s an awakening.
? When it calls to you, don’t look away.

Each piece in this collection embodies a fusion of rigid symmetry and organic horror—watchful, bleeding constructs, frozen in time yet oozing ominous presence.

Are these monstrosities ancient sentinels? Cursed relics? Or something far beyond human comprehension? The answer is left to those brave enough to collect and interpret their gaze.

This collection is an AI-crafted descent into the uncanny, blending surreal symmetry with the grotesque. 

Each NFT is a one-of-a-kind vision, a fragment of an ever-expanding nightmare waiting to be unveiled.

collections.name: AB SIGNATURE REINVENTED ORTHODOX CHURCH/ REAL ASSET
collections.description:
The places of worship imply in themselves, in addition to the architectural dimension, a very well accentuated spiritual side. The creation of such a project is a sum total of professional objectives shrouded in the mystery of the sacred, all passed through the prism of one’s own vision. The concept of this Orthodox Church was born in the process of meditation and came as a revelation of the reinvention of rule-driven forms.

I approached the challenge through the philosophical prism of the premise, following the religious canons. The building has all the component parts of the Orthodox Church, but also follows the orientation towards the cardinal points to ensure the spiritual flux. However, I wanted to integrate the exterior into the course of contemporary aesthetics. I have created an object of worship, defined by straight lines and regular geometry, including the dome as a fundamental element that inscribes the structure in the mainstream of the confession.
